name: FUANGVICH
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began riding at a young age. (Thailand Tatler, 01 Mar 2017)'), ('Reason', '"I grew up with horses and equestrian sport as my late father General Deva was involved with horses in Thailand. He was one of the main group of people who initiated the formation of the equestrian federation here in Thailand. I think [equestrian] is in my blood. On my mother\'s side, my grandfather was the first chairman of the polo club in Lumpini Park [in Bangkok, Thailand], so of course he rode a lot and so did my mum." (fei.org, 26 Feb 2018; Thailand Tatler, 01 Mar 2017)'), ('Coach', 'Maxime Livio [personal], FRA (fei.org, 26 Feb 2018)'), ('Memorable', 'Winning team gold in eventing at the 1998 Asian Games in Bangkok, Thailand, claiming team gold and individual bronze in dressage at the 1995 South East Asian Games in Chiang Mai, Thailand, and assisting in the development of equestrian sport in Thailand. name: Hermann Ludwig
bio: [('Beginning', 'He took up the sport in 1993, because he did not enjoy playing football with friends in Germany. (hermannhusslein.de, 2012)'), ('Reason', '"I was living close to a river and friends of mine had kayaks." (Athlete, 23 Jul 2012)'), ('Debut', '1999 for Thailand, World Championship in Augsburg, Germany (Athlete, 09 Nov 2010)'), ('Coach', 'Nicolas Noel [national], FRA (letelegramme.fr, 23 Feb 2018)'), ('Training', 'He trains in Europe. (Instagram profile, 29 Jun 2018)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNEW COURSE IN 2018He works for the Rowing and Canoeing Association of Thailand, and is involved in a project to build an artificial course in the south of Bangkok, in time for the 2020 Olympic qualifiers. "After qualifying for the Olympics in 2012, it was the push we needed for the [national] federation to get more funding to help develop the sport more in Thailand. So now to be hosting the [2017] Asian Championships, it\'s sent a message that Thailand is serious. We can have a real structure and go to the World Cups. And now we have the green light to go ahead and build a new course. It should be built by the middle of 2018, so for sure I\'m pretty happy about that." (Facebook profile, 18 Apr 2018; Facebook profile, 21 Jan 2017; canoeicf.com, 23 Feb 2017)BIG FISHERHe enjoys fishing and posts regular photos on his Instagram account of him posing with large catches. (Instagram profile, 29 Jun 2018)REPRESENTING THAILANDBorn and raised in Germany to a German father and a Thai mother, he chose to represent the country of his mother. He was the first athlete representing Thailand to compete in canoe slalom at an Olympic Games, when he took part in the 2012 Games in London. (canoeicf.com, 23 Feb 2017; hermannhusslein.de, 2012) '), ('Hero', 'French slalom canoer Fabien Lefevre. (Athlete, 16 Sep 2010)'), ('Influence', 'Coaches Sven Peiler and Pierrick Gosselin. (Athlete, 09 Nov 2010)'), ('Nickname', 'Ludwig (sportscene.tv, 27 May 2014; Facebook profile, 18 Apr 2018)'), ('Injuries', 'He suffered from mononucleosis in July 2011. The sickness kept him from training properly and affected his performance at the 2011 World Championships in Bratislava. (Planet Canoe, 02 Apr 2012)In 2008 he broke his ankle and dislocated his left shoulder. The injuries required two operations and two months recovery. (Athlete, 16 Sep 2010)He dislocated his left shoulder in 2005. (Athlete, 16 Sep 2010)'), ('Education', 'Mechanical Engineering - Augsburg University of Applied Sciences, Germany'), ('Languages', 'French, German, Thai, English'), ('Hobbies', 'Fishing, cycling, stand-up paddleboarding. name: NONTHAKON
bio: [('Additional Information', 'GeneralUNLUCKY INJURYAfter travelling to Azerbaijan for the world championships in 2018, he suffered an injury in training ahead of the start of competition and had to return home to Thailand. "I don\'t have words to explain to myself. I apologise as I am unable to compete at the 2018 World Championships as I injured my ankle while practising. I feel bad about not being able to compete as I travelled 14 hours from Thailand in order to compete at such a big and important event." name: RATCHANOK
bio: [('Beginning', "She was introduced to the sport at age five. Her parents worked in a factory that produced desserts, and she would often spend time there. The factory owners were worried that she could be burned by boiling water and hot sugar so they restricted her to the company's badminton court. (thestar.com, 21 Aug 2013; bwfbadminton.com, 15 Jan 2014)"), ('Reason', '"In the first place, I really didn\'t like it. My parents said that I should give it a try. After a few years I started to love the game and I realised that I could make a living." (firstpost.com, 12 Aug 2013)'), ('Debut', '2009 for Thailand, in Hanoi, Vietnam (badmintoncentral.com, 27 Apr 2009)'), ('Coach', 'Rexy Mainaky [national], INA (juara.bolasport.com, 09 Feb 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To win an a gold medal at an Olympic Games and to be number one in the world. (bwfbadminton.com, 15 Jan 2014)'), ('Memorable', "Winning gold in singles at the 2013 World Championships in Guangzhou, People's Republic of China. (bwfbadminton.com, 04 Apr 2018)"), ('Awards', "She was Thailand's flag bearer during the opening ceremony of the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. (thestar.com.my, 12 Aug 2016)In 2014 she was named Best Asian Sporting Icon by Fox Sports Asia. (foxsportsasia.com, 17 Jun 2014)She was named 2013 Best Female Amateur Athlete by the Sports Writers' Association of Thailand. (bangkokpost.com, 27 Mar 2014)In 2010 she received the International Olympic Committee [IOC] Inspiring Young People Trophy. (badmintonstar.com, 29 Aug 2013)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralHISTORIC ACHIEVEMENTSHer gold medal in singles at the 2013 World Championships in Guangzhou, People\'s Republic of China, was the first world championship title won by a Thai badminton player. At age 18 years and 187 days, the victory also made her the youngest player at the time from any nation to have won a world singles title, and the second-youngest player from any nation to win a world title in doubles or singles events. (SportsDeskOnline, 11 Jun 2018)OLYMPIC DISAPPOINTMENT TO WORLD CHAMPIONAt the 2012 Olympic Games in London she was winning 16-9 in her quarterfinal match against Chinese player Wang Xin, but failed to convert the advantage into victory. "It was my worst experience as a player." She came back from the disappointment to win a world singles title the following year, which was the first time since 1999 that a female player from a nation other than People\'s Republic of China had won a women\'s world singles title. "After I won [the world title in 2013], I felt the pressure. But a year passed and I felt that I was still human." (sportskeeda.com, 11 Mar 2016) '), ('Hero', 'Chinese badminton player Wang Yihan. (badmintonstar.com, 29 Aug 2013)'), ('Nickname', 'May, Nong May (bangkok.coconuts.co, 18 Apr 2016; thestar.com, 21 Aug 2013)'), ('Injuries', 'After competing at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro, she was out of action for six months due to a knee injury. She returned to competition in March 2017 at the All England Open in Birmingham. (indianexpress.com, 29 Mar 2017)An ankle injury forced her to withdraw from her quarterfinals match at the 2015 All England Open in Birmingham. "With the budget I have, I can only take my coach to some tournaments. That\'s why I haven\'t gone to the US because I couldn\'t compete without a mentor or someone I can consult with in a place far away like that. Even junior players have to travel with their coaches." (nationmultimedia.com, 01 Apr 2018)INCREASING INTERESTIn 2018 she managed to reach the third round of the Australian Open for the first time in her career. She said she hoped her performance would help increase interest in tennis in Thailand. "My dad is a tennis coach and when Paradorn Srichaphan was doing well [in the 2000s], he [her father] always had a lot of young players wanting to learn." name: YANNAPHON
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began bowling at age seven at Baan Pong bowling alley in Ratchaburi, Thailand. (news.tlcthai.com, 24 Sep 2014)'), ('Reason', 'His father introduced him to the sport. "When I was young, I wasn\'t even able to throw the ball because it was too heavy. I used to roll it around with my two hands. But the more I played, the more I liked it. When I started getting serious about it, my father became my first coach." (news.tlcthai.com, 24 Sep 2014)'), ('Coach', 'Paul Roberts [national], GBR; Tim McMahon [national], USA (matichon.co.th, 15 Apr 2018)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralHISTORIC ACHIEVEMENTIn 2017 he became the first bowler from Thailand to win a Professional Bowlers Association [PBA] Tour title, when he won the World Bowling Tour [WBT] Thailand event in Bangkok, Thailand. "This victory is very important for my country and shows we can reach world-class level competing against the best professional bowlers from all over the world." (pba.com, 06 Oct 2017; talktenpin.net, 11 Oct 2017; bowlingdigital.com, 06 Oct 2017)FOURTH-TIME LUCKYAfter winning a silver medal at the Asian Games in 2002 and bronze at the 2006 Games in Doha, he set his sights on winning gold at the 2010 Asian Games in Guangzhou, training five days a week for the nine months leading up to the Games. "There\'s nobody else in Thailand who bowls as often as I do. I can guarantee it." He was score leader early on in the competition in Guangzhou, but ultimately finished fourth. He considered walking away from the sport but decided to continue, and returned to win gold at the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon. "Had I quit that day in Guangzhou, I wouldn\'t be here today. It would\'ve been a stain in my life - something to always remind me that I set a goal and I wasn\'t able to do it. I really understand how a loser feels. It\'s the worst feeling. You gave it your all, yet you still can\'t grasp that thing you want. Still, I believe that if you keep trying, one day it will be your turn." (bangkokpost.com, 15 Oct 2014)FURTHER EDUCATIONHe has spent time studying at New York University [NYU] in the United States of America. (news.tlcthai.com, 24 Sep 2014) '), ('Nickname', 'Jojoe, Joe (Facebook profile, 23 Apr 2018; hilight.kapook.com, 24 Sep. 2014)'), ('Injuries', 'He missed the 2015 Kuwait International Open because he was suffering from inflamed membranes in his foot tendons, caused by excessively wearing flip-flops. name: NUNNAPAT
bio: [('Beginning', 'She was initially introduced to the sport at age 10 through her uncle, and later began serious training in 2008. (old.fai.org, 29 Jul 2013)'), ('Reason', '"At age 10, my uncle came to visit our home and brought his paramotor over. I played around on it, but I dared not start the engine. I started practising seriously at age 20, learning the basics and flying off a small hill. In 2011 I was able to join the national team." (mgronline.com, 02 Nov 2015; old.fai.org, 29 Jul 2013)'), ('Ambition', 'Outside of sport, she aims to work for the police or the military in Thailand after graduating from university. (mgronline.com, 02 Nov 2015)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralEARLY DAYSShe dreamt of flying since she was young, although her mother did not initially support her involvement in the sport due to its potential dangers. "My mum saw me compete in Chonburi [in Thailand] once and was shocked to see my flying because she was worried it would be dangerous. So I decided to take her up to the hill and had her put on the paragliding gear before letting her fly on her own. I wanted her to understand the feeling that I get when I am in the sky and can see the beautiful view below and all the people supporting me from the ground. She started understanding more and started supporting me more and with her support, I managed to succeed on an international level and became world champion. I am glad that I could make my mother and everyone else proud of me." (mgronline.com, 02 Nov 2015) HIGHER EDUCATIONShe initially took a nursing course before moving to Ramkhamhaeng University in Bangkok, Thailand, to study science. She then switched to political science in order to have more time for paragliding. "At first, I passed the nursing entrance exam and was studying nursing. However, I was concerned about having no time to practice so after two years I decided to change university and my field of study. I moved to Ramkhamhaeng University and decided to study science, but I did not have enough time to practice and attend lab classes at the same time. I then decided to change my field of study again to political science, which gave me enough time to study and train. Although I wasted time in the beginning it has worked out well for me." (mgronline.com, 02 Nov 2015) '), ('Nickname', 'Bee (nationmultimedia.com, 22 May 2017)'), ('Education', 'Political Science - Ramkhamhaeng University, Bangkok, THA'), ('Languages', 'Thai'), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationResultWorld Accuracy Championship1Individual Accuracy2017Vlore, ALB221Individual Accuracy2015Homyel, BLR111Team Accuracy2015Homyel, BLR2215Individual Accuracy2015Homyel, BLR117Team Accuracy2017Vlore, ALB8921Individual Accuracy2017Vlore, ALB22World Games2Individual Accuracy2013Cali, COL816Asian-Oceanic Accuracy Championships1Team Accuracy2018Sara Buri, THA3Individual Accuracy2018Sara Buri, THA17314Individual Accuracy2018Sara Buri, THA173Asian Accuracy Championship1Individual Accuracy2014Ranau, MAS5062Individual Accuracy2016Taldykorgan, KAZ6478Individual Accuracy2014Ranau, MAS50616Individual Accuracy2016Taldykorgan, KAZ647South East Asian Games2Team Accuracy2011Indonesia68922Team Cross Country2011Indonesia16923Distance Team2011Indonesia4704Individual Accuracy2011Indonesia89512Cross Country Individual2011Indonesia19713Distance Individual2011Indonesia149World Pilots Ranking Accuracy (as of 01 Aug 2018)2Accuracy Individual Ranking201818548Accuracy Individual Ranking2018185')]

name: SANCHAI
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began playing tennis at age five. (Athlete, 23 Aug 2018)'), ('Reason', 'His father introduced him to the sport. (Athlete, 23 Aug 2018)'), ('Coach', 'Veerapat Phokrakul [national], THA; Braen Aneiros, PAN (sportringside.com, 28 May 2018; Athlete, 23 Aug 2018)'), ('Memorable', "Winning the men's doubles title at the 2007 Thailand Open. (Athlete, 23 Aug 2018)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralDOMINANT FORCEHe and his brother Sonchat are a dominant force in the doubles Challenger circuit, the second tier of the Association of Tennis Professionals [ATP]. Entering the 2018 season they had won a record 46 doubles tournaments since they began playing together in 2004. As a result they have been referred to as \'the Bryans of the ATP Challengers\' in reference to US twins Bob and Mike Bryan, who are the most successful duo in the ATP\'s top tier. "They are our idols. To be honest, they are incomparable. They are far, far in front of us as players." The Thai twins say they do not mind the comparison, but would rather be known for their own achievements. "We want to be known as Ratiwatanas - King of the Challengers." (newindianexpress.com, 13 Feb 2018; sportstarlive.com, 12 Feb 2018)NATIONAL FIRSTHe and his twin brother Sonchat became the first Thai tennis players to win an Association of Tennis Professionals [ATP] doubles event when they won the 2007 Thailand Open in Bangkok, Thailand. In 2016 they became the first Thai male doubles team to compete at an Olympic Games. (nationmultimedia.com, 03 Oct 2007; 31 Jul 2016; tennislive.co.uk, 30 Sep 2007)FIRE ESCAPEIn 2008, prior to the Challenger Series tournament in Bordeaux, France, he and his twin brother Sonchat were forced to flee from their hotel because of a fire. As they were trying to escape through the smoke, they heard the voice of Yannina Ker, wife of Argentinian tennis player Lucas Arnold Ker, who was still in the building with her young son. The twins wrapped their heads with wet towels and gave towels to Yannina and her son, before helping lead them to safety. "It was a scary situation. There were no escape routes posted on the door, electrical wires were dangling from the ceiling, there was no emergency lighting in the hallway and we could barely see anything because of the smoke," Sonchat said. (sports.espn.go.com, 13 May 2008) '), ('Hero', 'US tennis players Bob Bryan, Mike Bryan and Michael Chang, Thai tennis player Paradorn Srichaphan. (newindianexpress.com, 13 Feb 2018; Athlete, 23 Aug 2018)'), ('Influence', 'His father. (Athlete, 23 Aug 2018)'), ('Relatives', 'His twin brother Sonchat also plays tennis professionally. (newindianexpress.com, 13 Feb 2018; sportstarlive.com, 12 Feb 2018)'), ('Injuries', "He suffered a back injury in 2018. (Samitivej Hospitals' YouTube channel, 04 May 2018)He sustained a minor foot injury in November 2017. (sportsarlive.com, 12 Feb 2018)He sustained a herniated disc in his back in September 2011 that obliged him to retire during a Davis Cup tie against Republic of Korea. (Athlete, 23 Aug 2018)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralDOMINANT FORCEHe and his brother Sanchai are a dominant force in the doubles Challenger circuit, the second tier of the Association of Tennis Professionals [ATP]. Entering the 2018 season they had won a record 46 doubles tournaments since they began playing together in 2004. As a result they have been referred to as \'the Bryans of the ATP Challengers\' in reference to US twins Bob and Mike Bryan, who are the most successful duo in the ATP\'s top tier. "They are our idols. To be honest, they are incomparable. They are far, far in front of us as players," said Sanchai. The Thai twins say they do not mind the comparison, but would rather be known for their own achievements. "We want to be known as Ratiwatanas - King of the Challengers," Sanchai said. (newindianexpress.com, 13 Feb 2018; sportstarlive.com, 12 Feb 2018)NATIONAL FIRSTHe and his twin brother Sanchai became the first Thai tennis players to win an Association of Tennis Professionals [ATP] doubles event when they won the 2007 Thailand Open in Bangkok, Thailand. In 2016 they became the first Thai male doubles team to compete at an Olympic Games. (nationmultimedia.com, 03 Oct 2007; 31 Jul 2016; tennislive.co.uk, 30 Sep 2007)CALL TO NEXT GENERATIONAfter winning the singles title at the TATP Pattaya Open in September 2017, he called for Thailand\'s younger players to be more determined to succeed in the sport. "I\'m happy to still be able to win a singles title at this age. But at the same time I\'m disappointed that the young guys still can\'t beat me. I want to tell the young players to be more determined and work harder if they want to play professional tennis. If they still can\'t beat me, it doesn\'t look good for Thai tennis." (nationmultimedia.com, 11 Sep 2017)FIRE ESCAPEIn 2008, prior to the Challenger Series tournament in Bordeaux, France, he and his twin brother Sanchai were forced to flee from their hotel because of a fire. As they were trying to escape through the smoke, they heard the voice of Yannina Ker, wife of Argentinian tennis player Lucas Arnold Ker, who was still in the building with her young son. The twins wrapped their heads with wet towels and gave towels to Yannina and her son, before helping lead them to safety. "It was a scary situation. There were no escape routes posted on the door, electrical wires were dangling from the ceiling, there was no emergency lighting in the hallway and we could barely see anything because of the smoke." (sports.espn.go.com, 13 May 2008) '), ('Hero', 'US tennis players Bob Bryan and Mike Bryan, Thai tennis player Paradorn Srichaphan. bio: [('Beginning', 'She began competing in long distance running in 2010. (janeruns4life.com, 22 Apr 2018)'), ('Reason', '"A co-worker asked me to run a half marathon for charity. (BRIC TV YouTube, 21 Mar 2016)'), ('Training', '"My workouts include some kind of speed session, either fartlek or tempo, a couple days of easier effort runs and double runs on some days, along with a long run, which can have pace changes or a steady pace on different terrain.
